english:
  title: Postface to a Gift for Dharma Master Uya Uncloud
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Tao-yin spoke to me thus: "The Way of the Buddha differs from our Confucian Way, yet among his followers, the virtuous ones we do not reject, but rather gather as friends. Now there is one called Uya Uncloud, an attendant to the Venerable Lazy Monk. He served the Venerable One with increasing reverence through the years, and the Venerable loved him dearly. When the Venerable passed into extinction and was cremated, obtaining relics which were enshrined within a pagoda and commemorated by stone, Uya Uncloud performed every service without fail. Then he sighed in lament, saying: 'When my Master walked this world, he opened my blind eyes and unstoppered my deaf ears, yet still I could not cast off my ignorance. Now my Master is gone, and in the Eastern lands there is none to compare with him. My darkness will deepen with each passing day until I become wholly blind and deaf. My Master's virtue was such that he did not disdain to travel thousands of leagues to Yan to meet Master Finger-Void, and to the southern Yangtze to meet Master Pingshan, questioning them to verify his understanding before returning to the true path. Though I regard my Master as heaven regards earth, yet he himself did so—why should I alone refuse?' With this resolve, he made a pact with his friend Xiong Zhongying to journey to China, traverse the sacred mountains, and seek out great masters like those mentioned—Finger-Void and Pingshan—to enter the correct Way. Since I have already given words of parting to Zhongying, I cannot presume to address Uya Uncloud again. Therefore I entreat you—do not decline."

    I replied: "Of the Venerable Lazy Monk's disciples, there were countless hundreds, yet few truly entered his gate, still fewer ascending to his hall. Only Uya Uncloud, attending him day and night, drinking in his presence for so long, might be said to have approached that hall. And yet he is not content, but resolves to wander all lands seeking a teacher—truly his dedication to the Way is earnest. But know this: the Way that can be learned and transmitted, explained in words and understood through metaphor, is not the ultimate Way. What dwells in the heart cannot be learned and transmitted, cannot be grasped through words and metaphor. Whatever can be learned, transmitted, and understood through speech—all this he has heard from the Venerable. What else need he seek? As for what cannot be learned, transmitted, or spoken—even with a teacher present, nothing can be done; it depends only upon his own realization. Why then does Uya Uncloud seek from others rather than from himself, from without rather than within his own heart? Yet who can say he does not know this? There is a reason his resolve is not daunted by the distant path to China. Having encountered such a teacher and studied with such earnest dedication, as though fearing he would not arrive in time, and now having lost him—it is as a child who has lost its mother. The deeper the love, the sharper the longing. The longer the separation, the deeper the sorrow. Since his teacher cannot be recovered, he seeks another like his teacher. When none can be found in his own land, he searches even further through all under heaven, determined not to cease until he finds one like his Master. How could he accept mere cessation through despair? His sincerity is earnest indeed, and also sorrowful.

    Master's virtue and learning shine forth as the beacon of our Confucian tradition. Ever taking it as his duty to refute heterodox teachings, yet not spurning Uya Uncloud—by this his true character is revealed. Therefore I write this postface and also compose a verse-tribute to send with him:

    *Billowing, billowing rises the cloud,*
    *Vast and trackless, leaving no trace.*
    *In this very tracelessness*
    *Lies freedom from attachment.*
    *East, west, north, south—*
    *It drifts where it will.*
    *Born from the smallest breath,*
    *It fills the six directions.*
    *Now expanding, now contracting,*
    *Its nature remains serene.*
    *When ten thousand things burst into bloom,*
    *This is the blessing of its rain.
  footnotes:
    - Tao-yin (陶隱) refers to a Confucian sage whom Gwon Geun revered, known for his openness toward Buddhism despite his Confucian orthodoxy.
    - The Venerable Lazy Monk (懶翁) was an eminent Korean Zen master whom Uya Uncloud had served and studied under.
    - Finger-Void (指空) and Pingshan (平山) were celebrated Zen masters of China whom even accomplished teachers sought out for verification of their understanding.
    - The phrase 'ascending to his hall' references the traditional image of progressing through stages of discipleship, with entering the hall representing deeper attainment.
    - 'The core philosophical tension here reflects the Zen Buddhist paradox: enlightenment cannot be transmitted through words or learning alone, yet seeking is essential. Gwon Geun acknowledges both the futility and the necessity of Uya Uncloud''s quest.'
